node.text:
My name is Isela Gonzalez, I am 22 years old, and I graduated from the University of Houston with a Bachelor of Science in Computer Science. I heard about the Girls Who Code hiring summit in January thanks to a classmate who shared the registration link. Without hesitation, I registered for the summit and prepared to make the most out of the opportunity. Because the event was virtual, it was easy to navigate, explore all the booths, and connect with recruiters. 

After the summit, I followed up with my top companies, applied for roles on their website, and prepared for interviews. Within a week, I got invited for interviews, and within a month, I received my first offer letter. 

I am now an Engineering Analyst at Wells Fargo, and I work with a team building an automated data management framework. So far, I have contributed with documentation for all the moving pieces that compose the framework, and today I am working on building a data pipeline using one of those pieces. 

My experience so far has been phenomenal because I am allowed to contribute, learn, and ask questions in parallel. The support I have received from my manager, team members, and other GWC new hires (there were 17 of us!) has made a  positive difference in my overall experience. 

My words of advice for young women attending the summit or looking for a job is to go in with a mindset of abundance — keep in mind that all of you are worthy of great things. Apply to every role you wish to with faith, and remember you have nothing to lose but an item from your to-do list. 

Ahead of our September Hiring Summit, we’re sharing stories of young women like @ise.gg__ who were hired thanks to our first-ever Hiring Summit this past January. If you’re a woman or non-binary technologist either currently enrolled in college or a recent college graduate, register for our Summit on September 15. #LinkInBio

Today’s #WCW goes to astrophysicist Jocelyn Bell Burnell. 👩‍🔬 

In 1967,  Burnell made a scientific discovery that changed how  we see the universe. While assisting astronomer  Anthony Hewish, she discovered pulsars — compact, spinning celestial objects that give off beams of radiation, like cosmic lighthouses. Even though she changed astronomy forever, Hewish won the Nobel Prize. 

We think it’s time that women in STEM like Jocelyn Bell Burnell (finally!) get her flowers. 👏 💐 Who’s your STEM superhero? Let us know in the comments below.

Ready to spend the day with Alyssa Carson? 💫  Check out today’s #IGtakeover.

Nicknamed “@nasablueberry,” Alyssa is the youngest person in history to pass all NASA aerospace tests (and at only 19 years old.) Alyssa inspires girls to break into the STEM field and aims to become the first human to travel to Mars. 🚀 

To get up close and personal with Alyssa, check out our #IGstory, where she’ll be hanging out and answering questions all day long.

Today is #BlackWomensEqualPayDay. According to @NPWF, if the #WageGap were eliminated, a Black woman working full time year-round would have enough for roughly:
👶🏾: 2.5 years of child care
🍲:156 more weeks of food
🏡:22 more months of rent

Of course, Black women aren’t alone in experiencing a wage gap, and many women are paid even less; Native American women are paid 60 cents, and Latinas are paid 55 cents for every dollar paid to white, non-Hispanic men.

While the wage gap is smaller for Black women in tech, it's still a problem. Our CEO, Dr. Tarika Barrett, offered advice for tech leaders on LinkedIn today (link in bio)

node.text: #WCW Meet Nora Al Matrooshi , the first Arab female astronaut. Nora is a 28-year-old mechanical engineering graduate from UAE. Growing up she always strived to go into outer space, and after being selected out of more than 4,000 candidates, her dreams are finally coming true.
